### Background
Addyston Pipe and Steel Co. v. United States, 175 U.S. 211 (1899), was a landmark case in antitrust law decided by the United States Supreme Court. The case revolved around the interpretation of the Sherman Act and the legality of certain trade restraints. The defendants, a group of pipemakers, were accused of engaging in anti-competitive practices that violated the Sherman Act. The case raised significant questions about what constitutes a lawful restraint of trade and the implications of such restraints on competition.

### Facts
The defendants were involved in a collusive agreement where they would submit bids for municipal projects. In this arrangement, when municipalities offered projects to the lowest bidder, all companies except the one designated would overbid. This practice ensured that the designated low bidder would win the contract, provided no outside bids were submitted. The government contended that this behavior constituted bid rigging, which is considered a per se violation of antitrust laws. The defendants, however, argued that their actions represented a reasonable restraint of trade and that the Sherman Act was not intended to prohibit such agreements.

### Theory of Harm
The core issue in this case was whether the restraint of trade was ancillary to a lawful contract. The government maintained that any naked restraint on trade is unlawful, regardless of its reasonableness. The defendants countered that their agreement was a necessary part of their business operations and did not harm competition in the market. This case highlighted the tension between maintaining competitive markets and allowing businesses to collaborate in certain contexts.

### Outcome
The Supreme Court ultimately ruled against the defendants, affirming that a naked restraint on trade is indeed unlawful. The Court emphasized that for a restraint to be lawful, it must be ancillary to a legitimate business purpose. This ruling set a precedent in antitrust law, clarifying the boundaries of acceptable business practices and reinforcing the importance of competition in the marketplace. The decision underscored the principle that even reasonable restraints could not be justified if they were not tied to a lawful objective.

