### Background
The case of **Bigelow v. RKO Radio Pictures, Inc.** revolves around the legal complexities of advertising and the rights of individuals in the entertainment industry. The plaintiff, Bigelow, was involved in a dispute with RKO Radio Pictures, a major film studio, over the use of his name and likeness in promotional materials. This case highlights the tension between commercial interests and personal rights, particularly in the context of the burgeoning film industry of the mid-20th century.

### Theory of Harm
The core issue in this case was whether RKO Radio Pictures had the right to use Bigelow's name without his consent. Bigelow argued that the unauthorized use of his name constituted a violation of his right to publicity, which is the right of an individual to control the commercial use of their identity. The implications of this case extended beyond Bigelow, as it set a precedent for how similar cases would be handled in the future, particularly in the realm of advertising and celebrity endorsements.

### Outcome
Ultimately, the court ruled in favor of Bigelow, affirming his right to control the use of his name and likeness. This decision underscored the importance of consent in advertising and established a legal framework for future cases involving the right to publicity. The ruling had significant implications for the entertainment industry, as it clarified the boundaries of commercial use of personal identities.

### Impact
The case is often cited in discussions about the rights of individuals in the entertainment sector and the responsibilities of companies in respecting those rights. It serves as a reminder of the delicate balance between commercial interests and individual rights, particularly in an industry that thrives on personal branding and recognition.

