### Background
The case of **Aspen Skiing Co. v. Aspen Highlands Skiing Corp.** revolves around the competitive dynamics in the ski resort industry in Aspen, Colorado. The dispute arose when Aspen Skiing Co. (ASC) refused to sell lift tickets that would allow skiers to access both its own ski areas and those of its competitor, Aspen Highlands. This refusal was seen as an attempt to maintain a monopoly over the ski market in Aspen, which led to significant legal scrutiny.

### Theory of Harm
The primary legal question was whether ASC's actions constituted an illegal restraint of trade under the Sherman Act. The plaintiffs argued that ASC's refusal to cooperate with Aspen Highlands was an anti-competitive practice that harmed consumers by limiting their choices and inflating prices. The case highlighted the importance of cooperation in competitive markets and raised questions about the responsibilities of dominant firms.

### Outcome
The Supreme Court ultimately ruled in favor of Aspen Highlands, determining that ASC's conduct was indeed anti-competitive. The Court emphasized that a monopolist has a duty to deal fairly with competitors and that ASC's refusal to sell joint tickets was an exclusionary practice that harmed competition. This landmark decision reinforced the principles of fair competition and set a precedent for future antitrust cases.

### Implications
The ruling had significant implications for the ski resort industry and beyond, as it clarified the legal obligations of dominant firms in terms of cooperation with competitors. It underscored the necessity for businesses to engage in fair practices that promote competition rather than stifle it.

